A mother and a baby have been rushed to hospital after being hit by a car in London. Police closed off the road after the incident this morning in Finchley, North London. The woman is reported to be in a life-threatening condition. The crash occurred this morning on a major A road that passes several schools including a primary school. London's Air Ambulance attended the scene following the crash and police remain on the scene. A spokesperson for London Ambulance Service said: "We were called at 11:18am today (6 January) to reports of a road traffic collision on East End Road, Finchley. "We sent a number of resources to the scene, including two ambulance crews, a medic in a fast response car, an incident response officer and a clinical team manager. We also dispatched London’s Air Ambulance. We treated two people at the scene before taking them to hospital." Police, who arrived on the scene to find the baby and woman injured.  The crash happened on East End Road, in Finchley. Finchley has a population of over 65,000 people, according to the most recent census. The area is mostly a residential suburb with three town centres. East End Road is a major road in the area and passes several schools, including Bishop Douglas School and St Theresa's Catholic Primary School. The mother and the baby have yet to be named. We'll be bringing you the very latest updates, pictures and video on this breaking news story. For the latest news and breaking news visit: Express.co.uk Stay up to date with all the big headlines, pictures, analysis, opinion and video on the stories that matter to you. Follow our social media accounts here on facebook.com/DailyExpress and @Daily_Express